129 /*
130 IMPLEMENTATION OF THE BUFFER POOL
131 =================================
132
133 Buffer frames and blocks
134 ------------------------
135 Following the terminology of Gray and Reuter, we call the memory
136 blocks where file pages are loaded buffer frames. For each buffer
137 frame there is a control block, or shortly, a block, in the buffer
138 control array. The control info which does not need to be stored
139 in the file along with the file page, resides in the control block.
140
141 Buffer pool struct
142 ------------------
143 The buffer buf_pool contains several mutexes which protect all the
144 control data structures of the buf_pool. The content of a buffer frame is
145 protected by a separate read-write lock in its control block, though.
146
147 buf_pool->chunks_mutex protects the chunks, n_chunks during resize;
148 it also protects buf_pool_should_madvise:
149 - readers of buf_pool_should_madvise hold any buf_pool's chunks_mutex
150 - writers hold all buf_pools' chunk_mutex-es;
151 it is useful to think that it also protects the status of madvice() flags set
152 for chunks in this pool, even though these flags are handled by OS, as we only
153 modify them why holding this latch;
154 buf_pool->LRU_list_mutex protects the LRU_list;
155 buf_pool->free_list_mutex protects the free_list and withdraw list;
156 buf_pool->flush_state_mutex protects the flush state related data structures;
157 buf_pool->zip_free mutex protects the zip_free arrays;
158 buf_pool->zip_hash mutex protects the zip_hash hash and in_zip_hash flag.
159
160 Control blocks
161 --------------
162
163 The control block contains, for instance, the bufferfix count
164 which is incremented when a thread wants a file page to be fixed
165 in a buffer frame. The bufferfix operation does not lock the
166 contents of the frame, however. For this purpose, the control
167 block contains a read-write lock.
168
169 The buffer frames have to be aligned so that the start memory
170 address of a frame is divisible by the universal page size, which
171 is a power of two.
172
173 The control blocks containing file pages are put to a hash table
174 according to the file address of the page.
175 We could speed up the access to an individual page by using
176 "pointer swizzling": we could replace the page references on
177 non-leaf index pages by direct pointers to the page, if it exists
178 in the buf_pool. We could make a separate hash table where we could
179 chain all the page references in non-leaf pages residing in the buf_pool,
180 using the page reference as the hash key,
181 and at the time of reading of a page update the pointers accordingly.
182 Drawbacks of this solution are added complexity and,
183 possibly, extra space required on non-leaf pages for memory pointers.
184 A simpler solution is just to speed up the hash table mechanism
185 in the database, using tables whose size is a power of 2.
186
187 Lists of blocks
188 ---------------
189
190 There are several lists of control blocks.
191
192 The free list (buf_pool->free) contains blocks which are currently not
193 used.
194
195 The common LRU list contains all the blocks holding a file page
196 except those for which the bufferfix count is non-zero.
197 The pages are in the LRU list roughly in the order of the last
198 access to the page, so that the oldest pages are at the end of the
199 list. We also keep a pointer to near the end of the LRU list,
200 which we can use when we want to artificially age a page in the
201 buf_pool. This is used if we know that some page is not needed
202 again for some time: we insert the block right after the pointer,
203 causing it to be replaced sooner than would normally be the case.
204 Currently this aging mechanism is used for read-ahead mechanism
205 of pages, and it can also be used when there is a scan of a full
206 table which cannot fit in the memory. Putting the pages near the
207 end of the LRU list, we make sure that most of the buf_pool stays
208 in the main memory, undisturbed.
209
210 The unzip_LRU list contains a subset of the common LRU list. The
211 blocks on the unzip_LRU list hold a compressed file page and the
212 corresponding uncompressed page frame. A block is in unzip_LRU if and
213 only if the predicate buf_page_belongs_to_unzip_LRU(&block->page)
214 holds. The blocks in unzip_LRU will be in same order as they are in
215 the common LRU list. That is, each manipulation of the common LRU
216 list will result in the same manipulation of the unzip_LRU list.
217
218 The chain of modified blocks (buf_pool->flush_list) contains the blocks
219 holding file pages that have been modified in the memory
220 but not written to disk yet. The block with the oldest modification
221 which has not yet been written to disk is at the end of the chain.
222 The access to this list is protected by buf_pool->flush_list_mutex.
223
224 The chain of unmodified compressed blocks (buf_pool->zip_clean)
225 contains the control blocks (buf_page_t) of those compressed pages
226 that are not in buf_pool->flush_list and for which no uncompressed
227 page has been allocated in the buffer pool. The control blocks for
228 uncompressed pages are accessible via buf_block_t objects that are
229 reachable via buf_pool->chunks[].
230
231 The chains of free memory blocks (buf_pool->zip_free[]) are used by
232 the buddy allocator (buf0buddy.cc) to keep track of currently unused
233 memory blocks of size sizeof(buf_page_t)..UNIV_PAGE_SIZE / 2. These
234 blocks are inside the UNIV_PAGE_SIZE-sized memory blocks of type
235 BUF_BLOCK_MEMORY that the buddy allocator requests from the buffer
236 pool. The buddy allocator is solely used for allocating control
237 blocks for compressed pages (buf_page_t) and compressed page frames.
238
239 Loading a file page
240 -------------------
241
242 First, a victim block for replacement has to be found in the
243 buf_pool. It is taken from the free list or searched for from the
244 end of the LRU-list. An exclusive lock is reserved for the frame,
245 the io_fix field is set in the block fixing the block in buf_pool,
246 and the io-operation for loading the page is queued. The io-handler thread
247 releases the X-lock on the frame and resets the io_fix field
248 when the io operation completes.
249
250 A thread may request the above operation using the function
251 buf_page_get(). It may then continue to request a lock on the frame.
252 The lock is granted when the io-handler releases the x-lock.
253
254 Read-ahead
255 ----------
256
257 The read-ahead mechanism is intended to be intelligent and
258 isolated from the semantically higher levels of the database
259 index management. From the higher level we only need the
260 information if a file page has a natural successor or
261 predecessor page. On the leaf level of a B-tree index,
262 these are the next and previous pages in the natural
263 order of the pages.
264
265 Let us first explain the read-ahead mechanism when the leafs
266 of a B-tree are scanned in an ascending or descending order.
267 When a read page is the first time referenced in the buf_pool,
268 the buffer manager checks if it is at the border of a so-called
269 linear read-ahead area. The tablespace is divided into these
270 areas of size 64 blocks, for example. So if the page is at the
271 border of such an area, the read-ahead mechanism checks if
272 all the other blocks in the area have been accessed in an
273 ascending or descending order. If this is the case, the system
274 looks at the natural successor or predecessor of the page,
275 checks if that is at the border of another area, and in this case
276 issues read-requests for all the pages in that area. Maybe
277 we could relax the condition that all the pages in the area
278 have to be accessed: if data is deleted from a table, there may
279 appear holes of unused pages in the area.
280
281 A different read-ahead mechanism is used when there appears
282 to be a random access pattern to a file.
283 If a new page is referenced in the buf_pool, and several pages
284 of its random access area (for instance, 32 consecutive pages
285 in a tablespace) have recently been referenced, we may predict
286 that the whole area may be needed in the near future, and issue
287 the read requests for the whole area.
288 */
289

527 /** Allocates a buffer block.
528 @return own: the allocated block, in state BUF_BLOCK_MEMORY */
529 1031388 buf_block_t *buf_block_alloc(
530 buf_pool_t *buf_pool) /*!< in/out: buffer pool instance,
531 or NULL for round-robin selection

703 /** This function registers mutexes and rwlocks in buffer blocks with
704 performance schema. If PFS_MAX_BUFFER_MUTEX_LOCK_REGISTER is
705 defined to be a value less than chunk->size, then only mutexes
706 and rwlocks in the first PFS_MAX_BUFFER_MUTEX_LOCK_REGISTER
707 blocks are registered. */
708 static void pfs_register_buffer_block(
709 buf_chunk_t *chunk) /*!< in/out: chunk of buffers */
710 {
711 buf_block_t *block;
712 ulint num_to_register;
713
714 block = chunk->blocks;
715
716 num_to_register = std::min(chunk->size, PFS_MAX_BUFFER_MUTEX_LOCK_REGISTER);
717
718 for (ulint i = 0; i < num_to_register; i++) {
719 #ifdef UNIV_PFS_MUTEX
720 BPageMutex *mutex;
721
722 mutex = &block->mutex;
723
724 #ifndef PFS_SKIP_BUFFER_MUTEX_RWLOCK
725 mutex->pfs_add(buffer_block_mutex_key);
726 #endif /* !PFS_SKIP_BUFFER_MUTEX_RWLOCK */
727
728 #endif /* UNIV_PFS_MUTEX */
729
730 rw_lock_t *rwlock;
731
732 #ifdef UNIV_PFS_RWLOCK
733 rwlock = &block->lock;
734 ut_a(!rwlock->pfs_psi);
735
736 #ifndef PFS_SKIP_BUFFER_MUTEX_RWLOCK
737 rwlock->pfs_psi = (PSI_server)
738 ? PSI_server->init_rwlock(buf_block_lock_key, rwlock)
739 : NULL;
740 #else
741 rwlock->pfs_psi =
742 (PSI_server) ? PSI_server->init_rwlock(PFS_NOT_INSTRUMENTED, rwlock)
743 : NULL;
744 #endif /* !PFS_SKIP_BUFFER_MUTEX_RWLOCK */
745
746 #ifdef UNIV_DEBUG
747 rwlock = &block->debug_latch;
748 ut_a(!rwlock->pfs_psi);
749 rwlock->pfs_psi = (PSI_server) ? PSI_server->init_rwlock(
750 buf_block_debug_latch_key, rwlock)
751 : NULL;
752 #endif /* UNIV_DEBUG */
753
754 #endif /* UNIV_PFS_RWLOCK */
755 block++;
756 }

827 /* We maintain our private view of innobase_should_madvise_buf_pool() which we
828 initialize at the beginning of buf_pool_init() and then update when the
829 @@global.innodb_buffer_pool_in_core_file changes.
830 Changes to buf_pool_should_madvise are protected by holding chunk_mutex for all
831 buf_pool_t instances.
832 This way, even if @@global.innodb_buffer_pool_in_core_file changes during
833 execution of buf_pool_init() (unlikely) or during buf_pool_resize(), we will use
834 a single consistent value for all (de)allocated chunks.
835 The function buf_pool_update_madvise() handles updating buf_pool_should_madvise
836 in reaction to changes to @@global.innodb_buffer_pool_in_core_file and makes
837 sure before releasing chunk_mutex-es that all chunks are properly madvised

965 /** Checks if innobase_should_madvise_buf_pool() value has changed since we've
966 last check and if so, then updates buf_pool_should_madvise and calls madvise
967 for all chunks in all srv_buf_pool_instances.

971 occur in parallel with allocation or deallocation of chunks in some buf_pool
972 as this could lead to inconsistency - we would call madvise for some but not
973 all chunks, perhaps with a wrong MADV_DO(NT)_DUMP flag.
974 Moreover, we are about to iterate over chunks, which requires the bounds of
975 for loop to be fixed.

977 only then update the buf_pool_should_madvise, and perform iteration over
978 buf_pool-s and their chunks.*/

3442 /** This class implements the rules for fetching the pages from the buffer
3443 pool depending on the context. It will set the page latches as requested,
3444 detect and handle stale reads and initiate read requests if required. */
3445 template <typename T>
3446 struct Buf_fetch {
3447 public:
3448 /** Constructor.
3449 @param[in] page_id ID of page to fetch.
3450 @param[in] page_size Size of page on disk. */
3451 1995153390 Buf_fetch(const page_id_t &page_id, const page_size_t &page_size) noexcept
3452 1995153390 : m_page_id(page_id),
3453 1995153390 m_page_size(page_size),
3454 1995153390 m_is_temp_space(fsp_is_system_temporary(page_id.space())),
3455 2378196640 m_buf_pool(buf_pool_get(m_page_id)),
3456 1995188114 m_trx(innobase_get_trx_for_slow_log()) {}
3457
3458 /** For fetching a single page.
3459 @return block from pool on success or nullptr on failure. */
3460 buf_block_t *single_page();
3461
3462 private:
3463 /** Lookup page in the hash table.
3464 @return block if found or nullptr if not found. */
3465 buf_block_t *lookup();
3466
3467 /** Get page if it's in the buffer pool or set a watch on it.
3468 @return block that is being watched or nullptr. */
3469 buf_block_t *is_on_watch();
3470
3471 /** Initiate a read request from persistent store. */
3472 void read_page();
3473
3474 dberr_t zip_page_handler(buf_block_t *&fix_block);
3475
3476 /** Check block state.
3477 @return DB_SUCCESS or error code. */
3478 dberr_t check_state(buf_block_t *&block);
3479
3480 /** Temporary table pages have different latching rules because they are
3481 not redo logged.
3482 @param[in,out] block Temporary tablespace to fetch. */
3483 void temp_space_page_handler(buf_block_t *block);
3484
3485 /** Add the page to the mini-transaction along with latching context.
3486 @param[in,out] block Block for which to add the latching context. */
3487 void mtr_add_page(buf_block_t *block);
3488
3489 /** Check if fetch mode is an optimistic fetch.
3490 @return true if it's an optimistic fetch. */
3491 bool is_optimistic() const;

3494 dberr_t debug_check(buf_block_t *fix_block);
